1. Ansible Installation & Setup
1.1 Installing Ansible on Control Node (Ubuntu/Debian)
# Update system packages
sudo apt update

# Install software-properties-common
sudo apt install software-properties-common -y

# Add Ansible repository
sudo add-apt-repository --yes --update ppa:ansible/ansible

# Install Ansible
sudo apt install ansible -y

# Verify installation
ansible --version
1.2 Installing on RHEL/CentOS
# Install EPEL repository
sudo yum install epel-release -y

# Install Ansible
sudo yum install ansible -y

# Verify installation
ansible --version
1.3 Installing using pip (Python)
# Install pip if not available
sudo apt install python3-pip -y

# Install Ansible via pip
pip3 install ansible

# Verify installation
ansible --version
Use Case: Install Ansible on your laptop/desktop to manage multiple servers, cloud instances, or development environments from a single control point.
Test Case 1: Verify Installation
# Check Ansible version
ansible --version

# Expected Output:
# ansible [core 2.xx.x]
# python version = 3.x.x
# jinja version = 3.x.x
2. SSH Key Setup & Node Connection
SSH Keys: Ansible uses SSH for passwordless authentication. SSH keys provide secure communication between control node and managed nodes.
2.1 Generate SSH Key Pair
# Generate SSH key (press Enter for defaults)
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "ansible@controlnode"

# Output will be:
# Private key: ~/.ssh/id_rsa
# Public key: ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub
2.2 Copy SSH Key to Managed Nodes
# Copy to single node
ssh-copy-id user@192.168.1.10

# Copy to multiple nodes
ssh-copy-id user@192.168.1.11
ssh-copy-id user@192.168.1.12

# Test SSH connection
ssh user@192.168.1.10
2.3 Configure Inventory File
# Create inventory file
sudo nano /etc/ansible/hosts

# Add managed nodes
[webservers]
web1 ansible_host=192.168.1.10 ansible_user=ubuntu
web2 ansible_host=192.168.1.11 ansible_user=ubuntu

[databases]
db1 ansible_host=192.168.1.20 ansible_user=ubuntu

[all:vars]
ansible_python_interpreter=/usr/bin/python3
